# Git Baseline

## Version control

- Use feature branches; never push directly to `main`/`master`.
- Keep commits small and atomic — one logical change per commit.
- Conventional commits: `<type>: <description>` — types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `test`, `chore`, `perf`, `ci`.
- Tag releases and maintain a changelog.

## Pull requests

- All production changes go through PRs — no exceptions.
- PR description summarizes **why** and what it affects; include a test plan.
- Keep PRs reviewable (prefer <400 lines).
- Reviewers check correctness, readability, test coverage, and security.

## Research & reuse

- Prefer existing repo patterns before adding new ones.
- Confirm library behavior via primary docs (Context7 when Focus selects it).
- Prefer battle-tested libraries over hand-rolled utilities.

## CI/CD

- Every PR must pass automated builds, linting, and tests before merge.
- Deploy in small, safe batches; maintain rollback capability.
- Automate repeatable builds, tests, deploys, and migrations.

## Test-first (when practical)

- Prefer red/green/refactor for new behavior and bug fixes.
- Do not weaken flaky tests; make them deterministic.

## Parallel issues

When running multiple issues: load [`.cursor/rules/issue-workflow.mdc`](issue-workflow.mdc) and the active slice in [`EXECUTION.md`](../EXECUTION.md).
